"# Appendix E — Reader-time introspection: meta-programming from source position

Between source characters and evaluable forms there is the reader. Chapter 7 introduced the reader as a callable verb. This appendix goes deeper — how source positions are attached to forms, how they travel through the pipeline, and how you can meta-program using position information.

## E.1 The source-position record

Every form the reader produces carries a `:pos` field:

```scheme
(:filename \"my-cart.slat\"
 :line 12
 :column 3
 :end-line 12
 :end-column 45
 :offset 234
 :length 42)
```

Seven sub-fields. Filename, start line, start column, end line, end column, byte offset, byte length. Together they identify exactly where in the source the form came from.

Access via `form-pos`:

```scheme
(form-pos my-form)
;; => (:filename \"my-cart.slat\" :line 12 :column 3 ...)
```

## E.2 Position through the pipeline

The reader attaches positions. The macro expander preserves them — an expanded form carries the position of the source form that produced it. The interpreter references them — errors during evaluation reference the position.

This means when an error happens deep in a computation, the error record's `:location` field points at the exact source token that started the trouble.

```scheme
(some-verb 42 (crdr '(1 2 3)))
;; error: unknown verb: crdr
;; at my-cart.slat:12:15-12:20
```

The 12:15-12:20 span is derived from the position on the `crdr` symbol. You know exactly which characters to look at.

## E.3 Reader macros

Motoi's reader has a small set of reader macros — special syntax that expands at read time:

- `'` → `(quote ...)` — quote the next form
- `` ` `` → `(quasiquote ...)` — quasiquote
- `,` → `(unquote ...)` — unquote
- `,@` → `(unquote-splicing ...)` — splice
- `#t #f` → boolean literals
- `#\\c` → character literal
- `#(...)` → vector literal

Each reader macro is a small transformation from character sequence to form. The result carries a position pointing at the reader-macro characters.

## E.4 Meta-programming at read time

Some code-generation tasks are cleanest at read time. If you have a preprocessor that consumes source and emits source, use the reader:

```scheme
(define (preprocess src)
  (let ((forms (parse src)))
    (map preprocess-form forms)))

(define (preprocess-form form)
  ;; walk the form, transform it, return new form
  ...)
```

Now you have a source-to-source transformation pipeline. Read, transform, emit. The transformed forms can be evaluated or written to a new file.

