## E.17 A worked example — a position-aware error printer

```scheme
(define (pretty-position pos)
  (string-append
    (or (assoc :filename pos) \"?\")
    \":\"
    (number->string (or (assoc :line pos) 0))
    \":\"
    (number->string (or (assoc :column pos) 0))))

(define (pretty-error-with-position err)
  (string-append
    (error-message err)
    \"\\n  at \"
    (pretty-position (error-location err))))
```

Ten lines. Any error, printed with a clean file:line:column tag.

## E.18 Custom reader hooks

Motoi lets you register reader hooks — callbacks fired for every form the reader produces. Useful for logging, static analysis, or preprocessing.

```scheme
(register-reader-hook
  (lambda (form pos)
    (when (and (pair? form) (eq? 'define (car form)))
      (display (string-append \"defining \" (symbol->string (cadr form)))))))
```

Now every `define` is announced as it is read. Small tool, useful for auditing what a file introduces.

## E.19 A truly deep dive — reader as a design lens

Some Scheme dialects treat the reader as a place for creativity. Custom reader macros can introduce new syntax without changing the interpreter.

Motoi is conservative here. The base reader macros are minimal (quote, quasiquote, unquote, boolean, char, vector). Extensions are possible but discouraged for durability reasons — custom reader macros make source files unreadable to tools that do not know about them.

If you need syntactic sugar, prefer regular macros over reader macros. Regular macros are visible to the standard reader; reader macros require special reader configuration.

