## E.24 Deep-seed — the position schema in one place

For reference:

```
:filename    string  — source file path
:line        int     — 1-indexed start line
:column      int     — 1-indexed start column
:end-line    int     — 1-indexed end line
:end-column  int     — 1-indexed end column (exclusive)
:offset      int     — 0-indexed byte offset from start of file
:length      int     — byte length of the token span
```

Seven fields. Filename is a string. Everything else is integer. If any field is missing (say the reader was called on a string with no filename), that field is nil.

## E.25 Deep-seed — the meta-programming use case

If you are writing a code generator, using the reader lets you build up forms as data:

```scheme
(define (generate-getter-form field-name)
  `(define (,(string->symbol (string-append \"get-\" field-name)) rec)
     (record-field rec ',(string->symbol field-name))))
```

The generated form is a normal Scheme form. You can eval it, emit it to a file, splice it into a `begin`.

For each field in a record type, generate a getter. Twenty lines produces getters for a hundred fields. That is the meta-programming power the reader unlocks.

## E.26 Deep-seed — the reader as a linter

You can walk parsed forms for style violations before evaluation.

```scheme
(define (lint form)
  (let ((issues '()))
    (walk form
      (lambda (subform pos)
        (when (looks-like-anti-pattern? subform)
          (set! issues (cons (list :pos pos :form subform) issues)))))
    issues))
```

Given a source string, walk every form and every subform. When you spot an anti-pattern, record its position. Return the list of issues.

That is a linter, built from reader-time introspection. No separate tool. No new configuration. Just a Scheme walk over forms.

## E.27 A closing note

Reader-time introspection is a specialty. Most Motoi programmers will never write a custom reader macro or a source-transformation pipeline. But when you need those tools, they are there, and the primitives are the same primitives you use for everyday debugging.

The reader is a verb. Forms are data. Positions are metadata. Every rule from the rest of the book applies.

Onward to Appendix F.

## E.28 One more useful pattern

If you are generating documentation from source, walking the parsed forms is often cleaner than string-processing.

```scheme
(define (extract-defines src)
  (let ((forms (parse src)))
    (filter
      (lambda (f) (and (pair? f) (eq? 'define (car f))))
      forms)))

(extract-defines (read-file \"my-module.scm\"))
;; => list of every top-level (define ...) in the file
```

Now you can extract just the defines, project their names and docstrings, and produce a module reference. All via reader-time introspection.

