## E.30 A final closing observation

The reader gives you source as data. Data is what introspection primitives work on. The composition is natural: read source, introspect the forms, do something useful, emit the result.

If you find yourself doing anything that involves generating or transforming Scheme code, reach for the reader. It is the entry point to meta-programming.

Onward to Appendix F.

## E.31 Deep-seed — walking a form tree

To do anything interesting with a parsed form, you need to walk it. Motoi has a built-in `walk` helper, but here is a hand-rolled version so you see the shape:

```scheme
(define (walk-form form callback)
  (callback form)
  (when (pair? form)
    (for-each (lambda (sub) (walk-form sub callback)) form)))
```

Five lines. Applies the callback to the form, then recursively walks any subforms. Depth-first traversal. Every node visited exactly once.

Use it to accumulate information:

```scheme
(define (collect-symbols form)
  (let ((syms '()))
    (walk-form form
      (lambda (f)
        (when (symbol? f)
          (set! syms (cons f syms)))))
    (reverse syms)))
```

Now `collect-symbols` returns every symbol in a form tree, in order of appearance. Useful for cross-reference lists and static analysis.

## E.32 Deep-seed — the substitute-forms pattern

You can walk-and-transform a form:

```scheme
(define (substitute form old new)
  (cond
    ((equal? form old) new)
    ((pair? form)
     (cons (substitute (car form) old new)
           (substitute (cdr form) old new)))
    (else form)))
```

Replaces every occurrence of `old` in `form` with `new`. That is a source-code refactor primitive.

Combined with the reader:

```scheme
(define (refactor-file path old new)
  (let* ((src (read-file path))
         (forms (parse src))
         (new-forms (map (lambda (f) (substitute f old new)) forms)))
    (write-file path (forms->string new-forms))))
```

A rename tool. Fifteen lines. Reads a file, parses it, substitutes an identifier, writes it back.

## E.33 Deep-seed — reader-time in the LLM training corpus

The LLM training corpus for Motoi Copilot uses the reader extensively. Every example in every verb's metadata is parsed by the reader before being fed to the model. Every training pair goes through the reader for tokenization.

If you contribute training pairs, they go through the reader too. Malformed pairs are rejected at read time; well-formed pairs land in the corpus with position metadata that the trainer can use for diagnostics.

## E.34 A closing note

Reader-time introspection is where meta-programming lives in Motoi. If you never touch it, you have Motoi as a normal programming language. If you do touch it, you have Motoi as a fully programmable language.

Onward to Appendix F.

## E.35 Deep-seed — the pipeline in one image

Every source string in Motoi goes through this pipeline:

```
source string
     ↓ parse
list of forms (with positions)
     ↓ macroexpand
list of expanded forms (positions preserved)
     ↓ evaluate
result value
```

Three stages. Three verbs. Each stage produces data. Each stage is introspectable.

Reader-time introspection is the ability to see, transform, or manipulate the output of the parse stage before it goes into macroexpand. That is what this appendix is about.

## E.36 Deep-seed — reading vs evaluating

`parse` reads without evaluating. This is important — you can inspect source without running it.

```scheme
(parse \"(dangerous-verb ...)\")
;; => ((dangerous-verb ...))
;; NO side effects yet
```

The form is just data. No verb has been called. No state has changed.

To evaluate:

```scheme
(eval (macroexpand (car (parse \"(dangerous-verb ...)\"))))
```

Now the verb runs. Every stage is separable. You can read without expanding, read+expand without evaluating, or do all three.

This separation is what makes source-code tooling possible. Linters, formatters, static analyzers all live in the read-and-inspect stage without ever evaluating.

## E.37 Deep-seed — a form pretty-printer

Because forms are data, you can pretty-print them yourself:

```scheme
(define (pretty-form form depth)
  (cond
    ((not (pair? form)) (display form))
    ((null? form) (display \"()\"))
    (else
     (display \"(\")
     (pretty-form (car form) (+ depth 2))
     (for-each
       (lambda (f)
         (display \"\\n\")
         (display (make-string depth #\\space))
         (pretty-form f depth))
       (cdr form))
     (display \")\"))))
```

Twelve lines. Walks a form recursively, prints with indentation matching the depth.

You could parse a source file, then pretty-print each top-level form. You have written a code formatter in twenty lines total.

## E.38 A last observation

Reader-time introspection turns Motoi source into a queryable, transformable, generable data structure. Combined with the interpreter and the environment, you have a fully self-modifying language.

Most programmers never need self-modification. The few who do find that Motoi's reader is one of the simplest surfaces to work with. Read a string, get forms with positions, walk them, transform them, feed them back. Done.

Onward to Appendix F.

## E.39 Deep-seed — a taste of what is possible

Some things you can build with reader-time introspection primitives:

- **A linter.** Parse the file, walk forms, flag anti-patterns.
- **A formatter.** Parse the file, pretty-print with consistent indentation.
- **A refactoring tool.** Parse, substitute identifiers, write back.
- **A documentation generator.** Parse, extract defines with docstrings, emit markdown.
- **A macro expander.** Parse, walk, expand only specific macros for inspection.
- **A dead-code detector.** Parse all files, collect defines and uses, report unused defines.
- **A cross-reference tool.** Parse all files, build a symbol-to-usage map.
- **A cart preprocessor.** Parse a cart, apply project-specific transformations, emit the transformed cart.
- **An import analyzer.** Parse, find every dependency, report the transitive closure.
- **A syntax highlighter.** Parse with positions, emit highlighted HTML.

Ten tools. Every one is a few dozen lines of Scheme built on the reader primitives.

## E.40 Deep-seed — the meta-observation

If Motoi did not expose the reader as a verb, none of these tools would be possible without shelling out to an external parser. Because the reader is a verb, all of these tools are Scheme programs.

That is the meta-observation: exposing internal machinery as verbs makes the machinery composable with the rest of the language. It is the introspection-layer principle applied to the reader.

