## E.42 A last worked example — the annotated pretty-printer

Combining reader positions with a pretty-printer gives you an annotated source viewer:

```scheme
(define (annotated-print form)
  (let ((pos (form-pos form)))
    (display (string-append \"[\" (pretty-position pos) \"] \"))
    (pretty-form form 0)
    (newline)))

(for-each annotated-print (parse (read-file \"my-cart.slat\") :filename \"my-cart.slat\"))
```

Prints every top-level form with its source position tag. Useful for reviewing a file's structure at a glance.

## E.43 The truly final closing

Reader-time introspection completes the picture. Every stage of the pipeline is a verb; every verb returns data; every data return is introspectable. From source string to final value, nothing is opaque.

Onward to Appendix F.

## E.44 One more note

The reader's exposure as a verb is small in code but big in consequence. It is what makes Motoi programmable at every level, from single expressions to whole cart transformations.

Onward.

