## E.46 Deep-seed — the source-map integration

For runtimes that emit source maps (browser bundles, transpiled targets), the reader's position info integrates with the source map.

A position `:filename \"my-cart.slat\" :line 12 :column 3` becomes a source-map entry pointing at that location. When the bundled runtime raises an error, the browser dev tools can show you the original source location.

Motoi's runtime maintains this correspondence. If your cart is bundled and shipped to a browser, position information survives the bundling. Debugging in the browser dev tools shows your original SLAT files, not the transpiled output.

This is worth calling out because most languages lose position information through bundling. Motoi preserves it end-to-end.

## E.47 One more deep-seed

The reader can be called incrementally. Instead of parsing a whole file at once, you can hand it a stream and parse form by form:

```scheme
(define (parse-incremental port)
  (let loop ()
    (let ((form (parse-one port)))
      (if (eof-object? form)
          '()
          (cons form (loop))))))
```

Useful for large files or for interactive parsers. The reader does not require the whole source string to be in memory at once.

## E.48 The truly final observation

Reader-time introspection completes the pipeline story. Every stage of Motoi's read-expand-evaluate cycle is a public verb. Every verb returns data. Every data return composes with the next.

That composability is why introspection works uniformly across the reader, macro layer, interpreter, and beyond. There is no privileged tier.

Onward to Appendix F.

